	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Cotton briefing is released</h1>

			
			<h4>
												14 September 2004
										</h4>

					</header>


				<div class="intro">

						<p> ‘Briefing notes on the reform of the EU cotton regime’ by CAFOD, CIDSE and CARITAS Europe, were released in February 2004. The briefing highlights the fact that the EU, whilst extending rhetorical support to the west African case for international action to halt cotton-sector subsidies, is in fact watering down the actions called for.</p>

		</div>
		
		
					<p> West African governments have called for a ‘phasing-out of support for cotton production with a view to its total elimination’, but the EU is only prepared to ‘pursue a reduction in trade-distorting subsidies within the WTO’, with only 60% decoupling currently being proposed as part of the internal EU process of cotton-sector reform.</p><p> The cotton sector is of great importance in western Africa , and rich-country subsidies are undermining the livelihood of most cotton farmers there. The USA is the principal culprit, but the EU’s cotton regime ‘also has a significant and measurable impact, with exports from Greece increasing by 209% between 1991 and 2001. Citing the recent ODI study ‘Understanding the impact of OECD agricultural and trade policies on developing countries and poor people in those countries - piloting an approach with cotton’ the briefing maintains that ‘EU cotton subsidies have a disproportionate and significant impact on developing-country cotton production ... due to segmentation of the world cotton market, Europe’s impact on west Africa is more concentrated ... than its total global impact’.</p><p> Turning to the Commission’s plans for cotton-sector reform the briefing notes that ‘partial decoupling as proposed by the Commission will not have any significant impact on the level of cotton under production ... rather than supporting west African demands for total elimination of cotton subsidies, the EU proposal will continue to support production at levels very similar to present-day production’. Only full decoupling would ‘remove the current high incentive to produce cotton and encourage a shift of production to alternative crops’.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			

<ul>

<li> 
<a href="http://www.cafod.org.uk/policy_and_analysis/policy_papers/reform_of_the_eu_cotton_regime" target="_self">CAFOD, CIDSE, CARITAS briefing on EU cotton-sector reform</a> </li>

<li> 
<a href="http://www.cafod.org.uk/policy_and_analysis/policy_papers/reform_of_the_eu_cotton_regime" target="_self">Executive summary of the ODI study (Marchs 2004)</a> </li>

<li> 
<a href="http://www.odi.org.uk/iedg/cotton_report.pdf" target="_self">Full text of the ODI study (March 2004)</a> </li>

</ul>
		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p> The fact that ‘partial decoupling as proposed by the Commission will not have any significant impact on the level of cotton under production’ is no accident, but rather an integral part of the structure of EU agricultural reform, one of the basic political pillars of which is that it should not lead to land abandonment.</p><p> The briefing claims that full decoupling would ‘remove the current high incentive to produce cotton and encourage a shift of production to alternative crops’. However, this underestimates the extent to which the process of EU CAP reform is based on a political commitment to avoiding land abandonment and implementing the process of decoupling in ways ensuring that it is avoided.</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
	</article>

